This '''flag was adopted by the [[Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic|Moldavian SSR]]''' on 31 January 1952. The flag has three horizontal bands of red, green (1/4) and red, with a hammer and sickle in the canton. As defined by the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of the Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic on the flag description:
{{quote|The national flag of the Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic consists of a panel of red color with a green stripe in the middle of the whole flag length, with the image on top of the red part of the flag from the flagpole golden [[hammer and sickle]]  above a five-pointed [[red star]] framed by gold border. The ratio of the flag's width to its length is 1:2 with the bandwidth of green to the width of the flag 1:4<ref>http://www.vexillographia.ru/moldova/index.htm</ref>}}

==History==
Between 1924 and the adoption of the flag in the 1940s, part of Moldova was organized as the [[Moldavian Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic|Moldavian ASSR]] within the [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Ukrainian SSR]], and used a red flag, with the gold hammer and sickle in the top-left corner, above the [[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] characters ''УРСР'' (''URSR'', Ukrainian initials of ''Ukrainian SSR'') and the [[Latin alphabet|Latin]] characters ''RSSU''. Between 1929 and 1937, the hammer and sickle was removed, and from 1935 on the Latin characters were removed.

In 1940, the flag was red with the gold hammer and sickle in the top-left corner, with the Cyrillic characters ''РССМ'' (''RSSM'') above them in gold in a serif font. 

