{{Unreferenced|date=May 2012}} {{Infobox song contest entry | song = {{flagicon|Norway}} "Intet er nytt under solen" | image = [[File:Intet_er_nytt_under_solen.jpg|250 px]] | caption = | year = 1966 | country = Norway | artist = [[Åse Kleveland]] | as = | with = | language = Norwegian | languages = | composer = [[Arne Bendiksen]] | lyricist = [[Arne Bendiksen]] | conductor = Øivind Bergh | place = 3rd | points = 15 | lyrics = [http://www.diggiloo.net/?1966no from Diggiloo Thrush] | prev = Karusell | prev_link = Karusell | next = Dukkemann | next_link = Dukkemann }} '''"Intet er nytt under solen"''' ("There's nothing new under the sun") was the [[Norway|Norwegian]] entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1966]], performed in [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]] by [[Åse Kleveland]]. In the Norwegian selections before 1977, all competing songs were performed twice, with big and small orchestra, but this is the only song to have been issued in two versions; Åse Kleveland's record using the big arrangement and [[Grynet Molvig]] issuing a version with the small orchestra. This song was Norway's best placing until 1985 when they won the contest with La Det Swinge, also in Norwegian.
The song was performed sixth on the night, following [[Yugoslavia]]'s [[Berta Ambrož]] with "[[Brez besed]]" and preceding [[Finland]]'s [[Ann-Christine Nyström|Ann Christine]] with "[[Playboy (Ann Christine song)|Playboy]]". At the close of voting, it had received 15 points, placing 3rd in a field of 18 - Norway's highest finish at the time.
It was succeeded as [[Norway in the Eurovision Song Contest|Norwegian representative]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1967|1967 contest]] by [[Kirsti Sparboe]] with "[[Dukkemann]]".
